South Africa: discussion on vuvuzulas at the World Cup
Perhaps the current look of the 2010 World Cup has been the bright new stadiums or the colorful costumes worn by the fans of each of the 32 nations competing.
But undoubtedly, the sound that defines the tournament has been the deaf vowel, which can be heard by spectators attending the games or by viewers.
The remarkable sound has sparked a debate about whether the vuvuzela adds or removes experience to the World Cup.
However, for international visitors and spectators, the sound of the plastic instrument has been a novelty.
Photo of the vuvuzela in Soccer City by Alvez and used under a Creative Commons license.
This debate dates back to the 2009 Confederations Cup held in South Africa, which may have been the first contact with sound for many fans of world football.
Some called for the vuvuzela to be banned in the stadium, saying it took away the game's enjoyment.
He said, "We shouldn't try to Europeanize the African World Cup".
Now, with a few days in the tournament, it has become an internet topic for those who complain about it, as well as those who defend the instrument and even those who criticize complaints about the vuvuzela.
Although there are some reports that FIFA may consider restricting vuvuzela due to television complaints, many believe it will move forward.
The criticism of the vuvuzela's buzzing proved to be rather funny for some, who turned it around to lighten their complaints.
