Egypt: A voice in the blackout, thanks to Google and Twitter
This post is part of our special coverage of the 2011 Egyptian protests.
Last night, following the total internet shutdown in Egypt, Google and Twitter (along with SayNow, a company recently acquired by Google) made a timely announcement: together they launched SpeakToTweet, a service that would allow Egyptians to call an international number and record a voice message that would then be tweeted from the @speak2tweet account.
All night, the Twitter account showed footage of Egyptians who learned about the service.
Due to the total ban on the internet, Egyptians probably learned about it through calls from their friends and family outside the country.
@monasosh is one of these users; his brother @alaa reported that he had taken advantage of the service.
So, I wanted everyone to know in case they didn't get any information about what's happening tomorrow, and I didn't want them to worry about us.
This time, I'm not afraid, like I want to say, 'Try it!
Stay with us!
Most calls are made anonymously, without the speaker identifying.
Another call from Egypt, available here, says the following:
Tomorrow, it will be history.
Tomorrow, we'll make history with it.
Tomorrow, the Mubarak regime will be over.
Tomorrow, we want you out of our country.
Long live Egypt.
Egyptians outside the country have also taken advantage of the service to make their message heard around the world.
Stay strong, Egyptians, stay strong, we love you.
This is an Egyptian-American speaking for all the Egyptian-Americans who emigrated here because of the brutal regime, stay strong: they are making us very proud.
I love you!
Anyone can use the service by calling one of the following international numbers and leaving a voice message: +16504194196 or +390662207294 or +97316199855.
The message will be automatically tweeted on @Speak2Tweet.
