Bulgaria: A day without Prime Minister Boyko Borisov
On 5 July 2011 an interesting challenge was presented to the traditional Bulgarian media: would they follow a Facebook call for "A Day Without Boyko Borisov" - or would they continue to report on the activities of the Bulgarian Prime Minister?
Reuters took note of the call on Facebook, and passed it through their cables, under the title that was very well placed with the organizers' intention: "Bulgars pray for a day without the busy Prime Minister Borisov".
The Commission has decided to take the necessary measures to ensure that the measures taken are implemented in accordance with the procedure laid down in Article 2 of Regulation (EC) No 1272/2003.
Image from the user of Flickr kaladan (CC BY-SA 2.0).
However, the Bulgarian media, with two memorable exceptions - the BGNES news agency and the Mediapool Internet site - did not follow the initiative and continued to include the Prime Minister in their articles.
Other bloggers also noted and wrote about the initiative, sometimes with ironic and sarcastic comments or titles for their posts, addressed to the Prime Minister.
In a very passionate and sad post, Nelly of Politics is arts was very critical of the Bulgarian media, asking why "I have to read news from foreign sites, watch foreign TV channels and prefer the opinion of bloggers over that of journalists".
Prime Minister Borisov himself announced that he was not interested in such events, and then immediately commented that he was paying the organizers the opposition.
One of the event's organizers, Mr. Atanas Palov, said this is ridiculous, and joked that if the Prime Minister paid enough, they could create an alternative event "One Day with Boyko Borisov".
The three young people (the other two are Ms Kamelia Encheva and Ms Valia Krusheva) who came up with the idea have denied political participation: one lives in Austria, one in Belgium and the other in Bulgaria, and they do not appear to have any political motivation.
It was chosen on July 5 because that day was two years since the 2009 election, in which Borisov was the winner.
At the end of the event, the organizers published an open letter, explaining that the initiative was not directed at the Prime Minister but rather towards the attention the Bulgarian media is paying to Boyko Borisov.
