Bangladesh: Indigenous or non-indigenous, that's the question
Almost 98% of the people in Bangladesh are Bengali and speak Bengali.
Minorities include chakmas, khasis, santals and other tribes who number over a million (about 1.2% of the total population) and who mostly live in the various mountainous regions.
The chakmas are ethnically Tibetan-Burmese, and are related to the Himalayan tribes.
According to history, they originated in Arakan (now Rakhine State of Burma), which hundreds of years ago wandered and settled in different parts of India and Bangladesh.
In recent months, many Bangladeshi indigenous peoples have taken to the streets to hold meetings, human chains and demonstrations, demanding constitutional recognition of their identity.
The 'indigenous' debate arose after some comments from a special parliamentary committee working to amend the current constitution to return to the 1972 Constitution.
There were no references to tribal or indigenous peoples in Bangladesh's first Constitution of 1972, which mentioned that Bangladesh would be the land of the Bengalis.
Members of indigenous communities demanded their recognition in the Constitution as "indigenous peoples" instead of tribal or proposed "minority ethnic groups" in the central Shahidminar in Dhaka, Bangladesh.
Image of Abu Ala, rights reserved, 29 April 2011.
Minister of State for Cultural Affairs, Pramod Mankin said:
It is not a question of whether indigenous peoples will receive constitutional recognition.
The debate is on how they will be recognized .
The government is reluctant to recognize indigenous peoples as indigenous as it questions the ethnicity of the country's native Bengalis.
Monjurul Haque on the Indigenous Bangla blog writes about the complexity of the situation:
"In the Constitution, all minorities are generally recognized as minorities, and through the Fifteenth Amendment, the current government has listed them as 'ethnic minorities' and no longer just 'tribal peoples'".
Giving a special and elevated identity to emancipate only 1.2 percent of a total population of 150 million by stripping the 98.8 percent right cannot be in Bangladesh's national interest".
He recalled the 4000-year-old tradition of the Bengalis in this land:
The people of ethnic Bengal are not settlers, nor are they foreigners or indigenous in their own native land and never will be
