This was a special event for Radio Martí.
This radio and television network is funded and overseen by the Broadcasting Board of Governors, the U.S. federal agency responsible for directing radio and television broadcasts in countries where government-independent media are scarce or heavily censored.
Most of Radio Martí's programming is clearly anti-Castro and supports U.S. policy in Cuba; most of its audience considers it a symbol of the political stalemate that the U.S. and Cuba have suffered for decades.
But this particular program focused on a group of Cubans: "bloggers", who do not define themselves as either dissidents or defenders of the fall of the Cuban government.
Participants discussed the increasing visibility of "bloggers" and social media in Cuba, and the particular way these new media are used on the island, where the penetration rate of the Internet and mobile phones is extremely low.
Orlando Luis Pardo Lazo, a photographer for the blog Boring Home Utopics, described the Internet "offline" as something that had been formed by the Cuban media:
This is the Internet offline , the Internet without the Internet ... blogs circulate through internal Cuban emails ... blogs circulate offline discs, on CDs, flash memory, DVDs, and, therefore, information is passed from one hand to another ...
Sanchez described his Blogger Academy  as a place where he teaches friends and acquaintances how to use the tools of recent media as they are really new to most Cubans.
She described: Get the most out of your mobile , as a workshop where she teaches participants how to "post" photos, videos and "tweets" via SMS.
I preferred the neighbor next door... but the Internet was not a decision.
The Internet was the only option.
We came to the conclusion that we would never be given a minute on the radio, a minute on television, not even a line in the national press.
So we had to use the Internet as the only civic expression.
Of course, the Internet is far from being a "perfect" way of expressing and sharing information.
For many Cubans, the Internet is still an unknown place and the simple concept of a blog or Twitter account is difficult for them to understand.
But for Cubans who can access the Internet or who participate in the Internet "offline" blogs and social networks have opened up a space for communication and expression completely independent of the government.
This is novel and very powerful, and while its social effects may be small and gradual, some "bloggers" believe that things are beginning to change thanks to technology on the island.
The Cuban poet and sculptor Antonio José Ponte, who also participated in the conversation, held this idea.
As information becomes more visible, people are now much less afraid to be informed.
All that fear is being relegated to new methods of communication.
* While this radio program allowed listeners to learn more about the particular stance of the new media in Cuba, the broadcast represented a rare encounter with the general media landscape in Cuba.
