Will Iran soon have its "clean internet"?
The Iranian regime may be losing its battle to filter content on the internet, but in the meantime it is trying new things - from slowing down the network, to developing a supposed "national internet" or "clean internet" (read Intranet).
Iranian members of parliament have also discussed a proposal to place blogs, comments and SMS messages under the same government regulation as mass media.
Iranian authorities see the internet as a real battlefield and view citizen media and social media as tools for a "soft war".
For several years they have claimed to have blocked and leaked millions of websites and blogs.
Now several bloggers have reported that Corporate Computing Systems of Iran says the goal for Iran is to be completely cut off from the world wide web once the country launches its own national internet.
Mehdi Jafari thanks to The Green Voice of Freedom
In October, many bloggers were happy to quote the statements of a senior official who said, "Filtering is useless".
Mehdi Jafari, referred to as the technology director of the Basij Student Organization (young paramilitaries supporting the Islamic regime), claimed that 17 million Iranians are on Facebook even though the site has been leaked in Iran... and that "the 300,000 websites of the Persian League are fighting against our religious and national beliefs".
Donayeh Eghtesad, an Iranian newspaper, wrote in 2010:
Two years earlier, Hamshari, an Iranian news website, wrote that "national internet" is an ambiguous term.
They quote a media expert who says that if this project seeks 100% of the international internet's filtering and expulsion, it is neither useful nor operational.
So, whose national internet is the favorite?
According to Hamshari, the Iranian parliament refused to give an initial $10 million five years ago, forcing the government to seek other funding.
And if the idea of the "national internet" wasn't ambiguous enough, Iranian communications minister Reza Taghipour launched another term: "clean internet".
He said they wanted to shield the internet from dirty actions and protect humans.
He said that at first, the internet was created for peaceful purposes, but now there are stains on it.
He explains the difference between a filter system and this idea of a clean internet.
For the first there is a blacklist (filtered sites), but for the second there will only be a whitelist (restricting the internet to permitted sites).
Now that we talk about a clean internet or even a Halal internet, we could also call it a virtual Frankenstein.
