Global Voices' second day review of the Citizens Media Summit
Group photo of the 2012 Summit
The second and final day of the Global Voices Citizens Media Summit 2012 began just as it ended the first night: with music.
As the audience woke up and sat down, a quartet of musicians, the group Sheru ni Sheru, marched to the stage playing the drum and dancing to the beat of the morning call.
Fully alert, the summit was presented to Boukary Konaté of Mali and Victoria Tinta of Bolivia, both winners of the GV's Rising Voices scholarships.
Currently, Boukary, along with others, is leading the Segu Villages Connection Project.
This project runs through each of the schools in rural Mali and seeks to create cultural ties between the city and the villages by teaching how to use the network.
Victoria Tinta grew up in Bolivia speaking the Aymara language and during college began using the Internet to mobilize the Aymara community.
Currently, Victoria works with a group called Jaqi Aru, which runs bloggers' workshops for Aymara speakers in order to strengthen the Aymara language's presence on the network.
The Summit was then divided into three groups of special panels.
Jillian York launched the provocative program titled "Are They Watching Us?", which sparked a debate about potentially justified surveillance and the needs for privacy and political freedom. Robert Faris, director of research at the Berkman Center for Internet and Society, explored the exchanges between law enforcement and transparency standards, while citizen journalists Afef Abrougui from Tunisia and Mohamed El Gohary from Egypt described the dangers and practical obstacles facing dissidents of government and corporate surveillance.
In another group, panelists met to discuss the importance of using citizen media to organize mass actions, especially focused on Kenya.
After a brief break, the Summit continued with a second round of special sessions.
Gilad Lotam, vice president of SocialFlow, moderated "Information Visualization", which explores the methods through which analysts and promoters gather, sort and project information in both activist and scientific contexts.
Rebecca MacKinnon, co-founder of GV, chaired a separate panel on citizen participation in the future of the Internet, and asked those present to focus on how ordinary people act when governments do not defend the people's interests.
A third group met to discuss the challenge of "creating an African network", and the things that are necessary to establish relationships and unity between local citizen media and the outside world to support the project.
After lunch, the Summit started two sets of open programs covering about a dozen different topics, such as China-Africa relations, women and technology, and open resources.
Finally, before the Summit ended with a night of music and a Kenyan barbecue, Global Voices paid tribute to its co-founders and organizers.
