Declaration for Internet Freedom
As many have pointed out, the world is at a crucial moment in terms of internet freedom.
In many countries, laws have been created to censor the network, while bloggers are increasingly at risk for speaking up.
Over the past year, organizations around the world have come together as never before to fight for internet freedom.
From the fight against SOPA and PIPA laws in the United States, to the global efforts to end the Trade Agreement Against Counterfeiting (ACTA), we have embraced a spirit of freedom and openness on the Internet.
With this in mind, numerous groups have recently joined forces to draft a Declaration for Internet Freedom, of which Global Voices Advocacy has been one of the original signatories.
To date, this declaration has been signed by more than 1300 organisations and companies, and this number continues to grow.
The text of the statement can be read below.
You can sign the statement here; you can also participate through different organisations, such as EFF, Access, and even Cheezburger.
The problem
We believe that a free and open internet can make a better world.
To keep the internet free and open, we ask communities, businesses and countries to recognize these principles.
We join an international movement to defend our freedoms because we believe it's worth fighting for.
We discuss these principles,  we will accept or refute them, we will debate them, we will translate them, we will make them our own and we will spread the discussion to our community  as only possible on the internet.
Join us so that the Internet remains free and open.
The Commission shall adopt implementing acts in accordance with Article 21 of this Regulation.
We stand for a free and open internet.
We support transparent and participatory processes for regulating the internet and the establishment of five basic principles:
Expression: The internet should not be censored.
Access: Promoting universal access to fast and affordable networks.
Opening: The Internet must remain an open network where everyone is free to connect, communicate, write, read, see, speak, listen, learn, create and innovate.
Innovation: Protecting the freedom to innovate and create without permission.
New technologies should not be blocked, and innovators should not be punished for the actions of users.
Privacy: Protect privacy and defend people's ability to control how their data and devices are used.
