Between 45 and 50 people live in makeshift huts in abandoned forests along Feher and Terebesi roads in Budapest, the capital of Hungary.
In June 2012, shortly before the event, the municipality of Budapest's X district asked these people to leave their homes.
Some of the residents, who have lived in these neighborhoods for decades, have built farms for their own livelihoods, while others have tried to make a living collecting and selling junk.
Several years ago, there were rumors that the city was planning to build a recreational park in the area.
Residents told atlatszo.hu journalists that Red Cross and Baptist social workers informed them of the eviction and offered to stay in their shelters.
The human rights organization A Város Mindenkié (The city is for all) criticized the forced eviction and labeled it illegal; it also said that the housing conditions they offer are worse than their current homes.
Albert Jonas, resident of the slum.
Photo by Atlaszo.hu.
In June, the blog Kettős Mérce wrote about the news:
One after another, municipalities announce the decision to destroy the marginal neighbourhoods but do not offer alternatives to help them.
However, shelters for homeless people offered as alternatives would not give them the opportunity to lead an independent life but would integrate them into a lifelong system.
At present, there is no policy in Hungary that allows for an independent start.
That's why people build these neighborhoods and try to create them outside the state framework.
In their blog, they wrote that the municipality gave two weeks to local social workers to find a place to live for these 50 people.
They also said that shelters for homeless people were not an appropriate alternative, as homeless people can live there for up to two years and without income would have nowhere to go.
The investigation by Atlatszo.hu showed that the municipality of District X asked social workers to solve the problem to support a real estate investment.
As deputy mayor, Tibor Weber informed atlatszo.hu journalists that the investor's plans, the Sidi Group, to build 900 apartments, offices and some recreational areas are currently in an advanced phase of authorization.
Civil rights protests and increasing media attention have apparently delayed the eviction, which now appears to have become a legal and negotiated process.
Many of the residents have already gone to shelters, others still remain in slums, but for now the process is on its way.
