An alarming act of censorship by private companies took place on September 26 last in Paraguay.
Two Internet Service Providers (ISPs) blocked the AbcColor.me website without a court order
Clarification from AbcColor.me
The controversial website is a user-friendly platform that generates content similar to the local ABC Color newspaper.
Any user can upload news (fake news and satire are welcome) as well as photos related to the news.
Once the content is uploaded the appearance of the article resembles that of the ABC Color newspaper, but it has a footnote clarification that the site contains fake news and user-created content.
TEDIC reported on the situation and criticized the move by ISPs as a violation of consumer rights and an act against the principles of net neutrality and consumer rights.
When users attempted to access the site from the Tigo Internet service provider they received a warning informing them that they were being redirected since the company had classified the site as containing malicious software and therefore simply denied access.
He was also blocked from cell phones.
After internet users were outraged and annoyed by this clear act of censorship by a private company, increased pressure on Twitter and even the Argentine Pirate Party expressed concern, Internet service providers unblocked the website.
Tigo Paraguay did not apologize or give explanations to users, they simply unblocked the site.
With the presidential elections approaching next April 2013, and after the accusation of former President Lugo online free speech is a sensitive and vulnerable issue in a highly divided country where political instability concerns many.
Now Paraguayan citizens know that their Internet service providers have the technology to quickly censor sites and are eager to do so.
As consumers and citizens they should ask themselves all sorts of questions.
