India: Dalit houses burned for caste marriages
On November 7 to 2000 people attacked three Dalits settlements in the Dharmapuri district of Tamil Nadu, according to the International Dalit Solidarity Network (ISDN) based on sources from The Hindu, IBN, Times of India and Countercurrents.
According to the newspapers, a nursing student from the community of Vanniyar (shudrá) married a name from the community of Aadidravida (dalit) in the colony of Natham.
After her father committed suicide for dishonor, crowds organized against the Dalits.
According to ISDN, the crowds arrived in large numbers in the afternoon, looted Dalits' homes and set them on fire with molotov cocktails.
Hundreds of homes were damaged and 1,500 Dalits were left without shelter or belongings.
It remains open and ambiguous that the greatest violence against the Dalits in Timiladu has been inflicted by thevars and vanniyars, two of the largest shudrá communities led by different political parties".
According to IDSN, Henri Tiphagne, executive director of human rights organization Peoples Watch, (IDSN partner) traveled to the area to assess the situation and offer help to children and said: "It was the most shocking of the incidents of caste atrocities I have seen in my life so far regarding the effects of the incident - a caste marriage that had been carried out with the knowledge of the police and protection that ended in violence with the attack on 430 houses".
