Rising Voices note: We are very excited to be able to collaborate with this upcoming event in early 2013.
This is a reprint of the original article in Spanish on the Living Tongues blog.
Lasting Voices: a workshop on technological media for endangered language speakers in Latin America.
Date: 7, 8, 9, 10 and 11 January 2013
Location: Library of Santiago, Matucana 151, Chile.
(Metro Fifth Normal)
Collaborators: Enduring Voices Project (Living Tongues Institute + National Geographic Society), UTEM University, the Chilean Image Foundation, and Rising Voices.
When ideas go out, we all get impoverished.
Half of the 7,000 languages on the planet are now endangered - a dramatic change in human intellectual history.
The basis of human knowledge is enduring, and for 99% of human history it has been passed down by word of mouth only.
However, it is fragile, mostly unwritten, and vulnerable to oblivion.
Digital technology can help document and preserve coded knowledge in these languages.
Objectives: to train 12 indigenous participants to learn how to create a register of their endangered languages, creating new language materials such as audio-dictionaries through computers, cameras and audio recorders and other technologies.
(All training will be given in Spanish.)
