Voting for the seven natural wonders of Africa
An annual contest has been launched to get the public to vote for Africa's seven greatest natural wonders, with voting currently underway.
The competition is organised by the global Seven Natural Wonders initiative and currently includes 12 sites from across the African continent.
Find out the preselected and other proposed candidates who didn't make it this year.
The Okavango Delta, Botswana
Hippos bathing in the Okavango Delta, Botswana, the largest inland delta in the world, by John on Wikipedia, CC license.
The Okavango Delta is the largest inland delta in the world, formed by the rains that fill the Okavango River.
The Namibian government plans to build a hydroelectric plant that would regulate the flow of the Okavango River, but ecologists fear this project will destroy the fauna and flora of the Delta.
Red Sea reefs, Egypt, Sudan and Eritrea
The Red Sea is a sea arm of the Indian Ocean located between Africa and Asia.
Its reef, which stretches for more than 1240 miles (about 2000 km), covers the coasts of Egypt, Sudan and Eritrea and contains more than 1100 species of fish.
Fish anthias in the Red Sea, from Wikimedia commons. Public domain image.
Mount Kenya, Kenya
Wall of Mount Kenya, by Radu vatcu licensed CC 3.0
Mount Kenya is the highest mountain in Kenya and the second highest in Africa, after Kilimanjaro.
It was covered by a layer of ice for thousands of years.
The Kenya Mountain ecosystem directly supplies water to over two million people.
The park receives over 16,000 visitors a year.
