The Baobabs Avenue is located in the west of Madagascar, in the Menabe region, between Morondava and Belon'i Tsiribihina.
Baobabs, up to 800 years old, are about 30 meters high and this particular species is endemic to Madagascar.
This place has been in the news lately because it was the victim of a forest fire that burned many newly planted trees among giant trees.
The forest of Bemaraha Stones, Madagascar
The Stone Forest known as Tsingy in the Bemaraha Integral Nature Reserve of Madagascar on Wikipedia (CC license 3.0).
Tsingy de Bemaraha is a nature reserve located near the west coast of Madagascar in the Melaky region.
This national park is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and its main attraction is the stone forest which is composed of sharp lapiaces originating from the erosion produced by groundwater and wind.
