Saudi Arabia: Public hunger strike in support of imprisoned activist
Saudi human rights activist Mohammad al-Bajady has attracted a lot of attention on Twitter over the past few weeks.
Al-Bajady is one of the co-founders of the Saudi Civil and Political Rights Association (ACPRA) and has been detained since March 21, 2011, after taking part in a protest calling for an end to arbitrary detention outside the Ministry of Interior building in Riyadh.
He was tried in secret and sentenced last April to four years in prison.
On 14 November, ACPRA issued the following statement:
In the last call from human rights activist Mohammad al-Bajady, which was on September 19, 2012, he told his wife that he would start a hunger strike after the call to protest against the abuse.
Our sources tell us he was held in solitary confinement.
Since he announced the hunger strike, no calls have been received.
On December 9, @freealbjadi announced a public hunger strike to support al-Bajady on December 10, International Human Rights Day:
@freealbjadi: Suffer what al-Bajady faces in prison and announce his hunger strike tomorrow...
Logo of the campaign "Save al-Bajady".
Dozens of reformist figures announced that they would be part of the public hunger strike announced on the #سأشارك_غدا_بالإضراب_عن_الطعام_تضامنا_مع_إضراب_البجادي tag, including activist Mohammad al-Qahtani, former political prisoner Matrook al-Faleh and famous blogger Fouad al-Farhan along with 200 others, while the public hunger strike in support of al-Bajady, which took place last March, had only 38 participants.
By strictly banning demonstrations, Saudi Arabia calls for new methods of public dissent, mostly by young people.
