GV Aymara at the VIII International Congress of Aymara Culture and Language
On December 6, 7 and 8, 2012 the VIII International Congress of Aymara Language and Culture Taxpachan Aymar Arusipxañani" (All Let's Talk Aymara) was held in Iquique, Chile, held at the Aula Magna of Arturo Prat University.
The organization was led by the National Academy of the Aymara Language (ANLA), the National Indigenous Development Corporation (Conadi), the Institute of Andean Studies, Isluga and Arturo Prat University.
The main objective of the Congress was to generate reflection spaces and proposals around the processes of recovery and revitalization of the Aymara language and culture aimed at strengthening the language, knowledge, wisdom and cultural practices of the Qullana Suyu.
The Jaqi Aru project received an invitation to participate and we attended three of the translators of Global Voices Aymarata.
There were teachers from colleges and professors from universities in Chile, Peru and Bolivia, students from Arturo Prat University and others.
Presentation by Esteban Mamani and Victoria Tinta.
Photo by Victor Paco Montevilla, used with authorization.
According to the program, the first day began with a Phawa ceremony (thanking Mother Earth), followed by a welcoming speech from the ANLA president.
After all this, it began with master classes, workshops on language rights of indigenous peoples , Jaqi Aru workshops: revitalization of the Aymara language, bodies, status, participation of speakers and communities with the theme:Ecolinguistics Aymara , presented by Professor Eulogio, of La Paz, Bolivia.
Finally, the subject of the discussion was also the experiences of education and teaching methods of learning the Aymara language and culture in urban and rural contexts: Looking at the universe with the eyes of our grandparents, presented by Luis Carbajal of Arica, Chile.
As on the first day, activities were held on Jaqi Aru workshops on revitalization of the Aymara language, bodies, status, participation of speakers and communities, with the following themes: Global Voices Aymarata: contribution to world history through translations .
The three of us are working on translations for Global Voices Aymarata.
When they heard our presentations, they were surprised and mentioned that few spread the Aymara on cyberspace.
When I heard those words, I felt very happy.
Workshop of Kurmi Wasi.
Photo by Victor Paco Montevilla, used with authorization.
The third day also began with master classes, this time with the theme: Metaforas culturales and personification of cultural elements in the Aymara language , presented by Dr. Ignacio Apaza, a professor at the Universidad Mayor de San Andrés (UMSA) and the La Universidad Pública de El Alto (UPEA), workshops and workshops on the theme: Methodologies for teaching learning the Aymara language and culture , which was presented by teachers Marisa Barrientos and Luís Gómez of the Kurmi wasi School, located in Achocalla, in the department of La Paz, Bolivia.
This is the conclusion of this long-awaited congress.
