Yesterday I defected from Assad's army
As part of our collaboration with Syria Deeply, we're publishing a series of articles that capture the voices of civilians caught in the crossfire, along with perspectives on the conflict from writers around the world.
Next up is a conversation between News Deeply and a 20-year-old man who defected from the Syrian Army's Sulas Military Base and joined the rebel side.
At your request, we will not use your name in this article.
We are in a house used by the Free Syrian Army deep in the mountains of Jebel Turkman, in Latakia province.
As the bombs rocked the windows, he shone a light on the complicated mentality shared by many of Bashar al-Assad's soldiers: men forced to serve mandatory terms in the army, desperately wanting to join the opposition.
"It's the first time I've seen a journalist or an American", he says timidly.
He says a shabiha escort was assigned to each new soldier, to make sure he didn't defect.
This came after a recent streak of desertions that apparently shook the confidence of the army.
"The soldiers were scared of the Free Syrian Army.
Many of them would like to desert, but the shabiha, staying with us, are watching us as security so we're not leaving".
The destruction of the Duma, Damascus.
Courtesy of Shaam News Network.
The young soldiers barely talked about the matter among themselves.
I was just talking about this with my family.
I couldn't talk to anyone else about it, even though we all wanted to go.
I would never do it... shoot into the air, give anything but fighters.
A lot of people do that. Those who look don't notice.
The officers have power and say, 'We'll succeed, we'll go home.'
But the fighters know it's coming.
He served most of his time in the army in Idlib, and was prominent in the Latakia mountains for the past two months.
At that moment he says, "I never had a vacation.
Before coming to our interview, I was worried about my safety by talking to him. How could the leader of the Free Syrian Army battalion who introduced us guarantee that his new fighter was not really a double agent who would report us to the regime?
"I spoke to your father in Damascus", the leader told me.
Trying to give me confidence, he said that given the security of the regime's bases, and based on physical ground, only the most loyal men manage to escape.
