Cuba launches expected immigration reform
On 14 January 2013, a historic immigration reform came into force in Cuba, which should facilitate entry and exit from the country.
According to the Havana Times, Cubans can now apply for a passport to travel outside the country for a maximum of 24 months, without having to apply for a special government permit.
The new regulation eliminates the previously required 'permit to leave' and 'invitation letter' and relaxes the rules for healthcare and sports professionals and those who have migrated illegally.
In August 2012, the author of "Eve's Other Eyes" referred to "internationalist missions", governmental projects to help other countries mainly in sectors such as education and health that also represent economic relief for Cuban professionals.
In another article (of fiction), the author narrates the departure of a father through the port of Mariel:
My father jumped into the sea, pushed himself over the waves and got lost in the horizon, leaving us an empty seat at the table and hopes of filling the caskets again very soon. My father left one afternoon, some time ago, maybe a little longer and we still haven't figured out exactly where in the Caribbean to throw flowers.
From 14 January 2013, Cuban citizens will be able to apply for passports at the offices of the Carné de Identidad and Registro de Población as well as the Immigration and Extranjería to travel outside the country without having to ask the government for permission.
Immigration and Foreign Affairs offices during the first day of immigration reform.
Photo: Courtesy of Jorge Luis Baños
According to a report by the Havana Times, which quotes the Immigration and External Affairs Directorate, a total of 195 sites have been enabled for this purpose.
According to the digital magazine, "it is estimated that the historic reform will benefit a large number of Cubans who, provided they can finance the trip and obtain the visa from the destination country, will be able to travel more easily abroad".
However, "it will not involve a mass exit from the island.
Regarding travel to the United States, an article published by the digital site Café Fuerte notes:
Cuba will allow its citizens to travel as emigrants and even welcome the Cuban Adjustment Act (CAA) in the United States without losing their rights as residents of the island within two years, a senior government official announced.
But some citizens, including high-performing athletes, will still have to apply for permission to leave the country.
In addition, the law includes an incision that has been questioned by several bloggers.
Fernando Ravsberg, author of Letters from Cuba, points out:
However, the H-clause states that they may not travel 'when, for other reasons of public interest, the competent authorities so determine'.
Such vagueness gives the officials absolute power over the citizen.
The shortage of teachers could be considered a reason of public interest and the Ministry of Education can feel empowered to prevent an educator from travelling.
Dozens of foreign media outlets have echoed the news and some users from other nations celebrate Cuba's immigration reform, although they note:
Cuban state television broadcast a television program with more details on immigration reform.
