Creating spoken dictionaries for indigenous languages
As part of the workshop "Enduring Voices", between 7 and 11 January 2013, twelve Latin American indigenous language activists met at the Library of Santiago, Chile, to explore how digital technologies can play a key role in documenting and revitalizing their native languages.
Organized and sponsored by the Enduring Voices Project, a collaboration between the Living Tongues Institute and the National Geographic Society, the workshop provided practical training on the use of digital tools at work.
Rising Voices also participated and gave a workshop on the use of citizen media to promote the use of indigenous languages online.
The main activity of the workshop was the creation of Talking Dictionaries.
This platform provides a multilingual online dictionary containing digital audio clips recorded by language activists currently working with the Living Tongues Institute.
Each participant received a technology kit based on their current needs.
Some of the activists received laptops, digital audio recorders and digital video cameras, tripods, headphones with the ability to cancel or decrease ambient sound and external hard drives to use in their work.
Participants examining the received technology kit.
However, the digital audio recorder was the one that played the most important role in the creation of the Spoken Word.
Each participant was able to record high-quality audio clips which were later edited into free programs such as Audacity.
The clips are tagged and uploaded to the server, hosted by Swarthmore University, where in the database they are placed in parallel and display the word in the indigenous language, English and Spanish.
Here we see Espiritu Bautista and his son Elmo recording audio clips of words in Yanesha, their native language, which is spoken in the central Amazon region of Peru.
At the end of the workshop there were nine new dictionaries spoken in languages such as Mapudungún, Tsesungun, Quechua Chanca, Yanesha, Miahuatec Zapoteco, Mazahua, Mam, Pipil, Besiro and the expansion of an existing dictionary in Ishír (Chamacoco).
Each participant returned to their local community equipped with the tools and knowledge to continue adding more words to the spoken dictionaries with a clear mandate to explore the best path for use in the communities.
Colombia: A long road to peace?
This post is part of our special coverage of International Relations and Security.
Colombian armed forces.
Photo by Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff on flickr (CC BY 2.0)
In the early hours of New Year's Day, the Colombian Armed Forces launched an airstrike against a Colombian Revolutionary Armed Forces (FARC) camp near Chigorodó in northwestern Colombia.
The airstrike came after Elda Ramirez (aka 'Mayerly'), considered an important member of the FARC hierarchy, called a man she believed was a drug trafficker interested in buying cocaine.
To support the peace negotiations, the FARC announced a ceasefire on 20 November.
However, the Colombian armed forces have continued military operations against the organization.
On 20 January, the FARC announced that they had suspended the ceasefire and instead proposed a bilateral truce.
The Colombian government's attack and the broken ceasefire prompted a variety of responses from Colombian bloggers.
For example, a blogger in Colombia Opina celebrated the bombings and explains why the FARC's fifth front was so dangerous (links inserted by GV):
The FARC's 5th Front was a sort of terrorist training school.
From Efraín Guzmán to Ivan Márquez, and from today's demobilised Karina  to the still-armed alias Manteco , they have passed through the 5th front of the Farc, an old and bellicose guerrilla structure that in the early morning of December 31 received another blow from the Colombian Air Force in the Operation Fortuna : a bombing that left at least 14 bandit dead and returns the hope of security necessary to the inhabitants of a strategic area such as the Axe Bananero, which also borders the corridor that runs from the Serrania of Abibe and crosses the route of the Río Sucio to the Middle Atrato.
In contrast, Camilo Raigozo criticizes President Santos' "happiness" with the guerrilla killing:
The regime led by President Santos has refused to stop the blood and death orgy that binds the Colombian people, by not accepting a bilateral truce of fire, not even for Christmas and New Year.
The insatiable bloodlust of those in power prevents it.
Horacio Duque, in Third Information, asks if the unilateral ceasefire of the FARC has worked (link inserted by GV):
It seems, from the data provided by experts who follow the fighting in detail, that in the first 30 days the success has been resounding.
Fernando Dorado writes about the need to extend the ceasefire:
If the ceasefire period is maintained or extended beyond the Christmas and holiday season, the FARC guerrillas would be putting all the pressure on the government to agree a bilateral ceasefire, which would give more impetus to the peace process.
It seems that the Colombian government's reluctance to respect the FARC ceasefire is intended to weaken the group both militarily and strategically.
The effectiveness of this strategy will likely be determined throughout 2013, especially as the deadline (in November) for a peace agreement approaches.
