The maritime border dispute between Bolivia, Chile and Peru
This post is part of our special coverage of International Relations and Security.
Map of maritime claims from Ecuador, Peru, and neighboring countries.
From Political Geography Now through Wikimedia Commons (CC BY-SA 3.0)
International borders are often erased by globalization processes, but in South America some maritime borders remain contested.
For example, Chile and Peru, neighbors who have enjoyed sustained economic development in recent years, still disagree about some 38,000 square kilometers of sea along their maritime border.
Bilateral negotiations between the two countries were first held in 1980, but no agreement was reached.
In 2008, Peru took the case to the International Court of Justice (ICJ), which, in turn, considered the issue in a public hearing in December 2012.
Meanwhile, Peru continues to argue that the maritime border has not yet been defined by any agreement, with documents signed in the 1950s only on access to fishing zones.
Lima also states that the maritime boundaries should run diagonally southwest from the land border.
Chile, for its part, maintains that maritime boundaries were agreed upon after the signing of the treaties of 1952 and 1954.
These imply that the maritime border should run parallel to the line of Ecuador, an agreement that Santiago claims Peru has respected for the past 60 years.
Supporting the Chilean position, weblogger Juan Vargas commented in Peru this Week:
The agreements of 1952 and 1954 clearly indicate and establish a maritime border.
They can be found in English at: http://www.state.gov/documents/organization/58820.pdf
Oscar Maúrtua de Romaña, a former Peruvian foreign minister, describes the arguments of both sides in a blog post by El Mirador, and concludes:
Peru and Chile, despite historical differences, share a common destiny.
A fair ruling by the court will put an end to the only border issue that casts a shadow on our bilateral relations.
It is reassuring that President Humala and President Piñera, 72 hours before the oral hearing began, have made a joint statement, in which they both pledged to comply with and implement the judgment of the International Court of Justice in The Hague.
The Bolivian coast awaits the decision
The dispute between Chile and Peru also has direct implications in other states in the region.
In particular, Bolivia is closely following legal procedures, and has previously stated that it plans to make a case before the International Court of Justice to facilitate Chile's access to the Pacific coast it lost during the 1879-1881 war between the two countries.
The final outcome in the ICJ case can add a new impetus to Bolivia's attempts to seek a diplomatic solution to this longstanding problem.
Regardless of the ICJ's resolution, democratic and diplomatic statements made by all parties have significantly reduced the risk of armed conflict between the parties.
This, in turn, has laid the foundation for the development of more creative solutions to end the crisis.
These include "a maritime zone of Bilateral Participation" proposed by Jilmar Moisés Córdova, who argues:
The maritime dispute between Peru and Chile can be resolved by establishing a Bilateral Sea Participation Zone which would divide the seas of both States and would be devoted to fishing, i.e. the exploitation of living resources by vessels of up to a certain tonnage of Peruvian and Chilean peoples.
For example, Argentina and Uruguay maintain a treaty similar to this one that delimits their sovereign seas.
Cordoba also considers that this alternative could give both countries the opportunity to explore and benefit from minerals, oil and other resources.
He also believes that the bilateral Maritime Zone could offer alternative options for the aspirations of a coastline for Bolivia.
