Dancing to the beat of history with marrabenta in Mozambique
This post was first published on Afribuku, a blog about contemporary African culture.
It is often said that Mozambicans start the year "marrumbling".
That's because every year, in early February, the country's most representative festival, the Marrabenta Festival, takes place.
Everywhere you go, you hear "teka, teka! , the expression used while dancing is ferocious, it has a contagious rhythm and it becomes difficult not to get carried away.
But in Mozambique, talking about the music of the beat is also something serious, because at every hypnotic rhythm, it resonates with the colonial past and the identity of the country.
The Marrabenta Music Festival This time, from February 1 to 3, 2013, the famous Congolese composer and singer Sam Mangwana and other Mozambican musicians such as Dilon Djindji, Radio Marrabenta, Xidimingwana, Orquesta Djambo or Cheny Wa Gune, performed at the sixth edition of this festival held in the city of Maputo and in the villages of Marracuene and Matalene.
As every year, a train with live music left from Maputo and brought free musicians and audiences to the village of Marracuene.
An hour and a half away on the "Marrabenta Train", people also joined in the celebration of Gwaza Muthini, which coincides with the date.
It's a train of twitches.
Photo by Litho Paulo David Sithoe on Facebook.
Resistance music
The Gwaza Muthini ceremony commemorates the famous Battle of Marracuene, which took place on February 2, 1895. In this battle, the warriors of the Gaza Empire, under the command of Ngumgunhane, resisted the Portuguese colonial army.
The men of Ngumgunhane lost the battle and this was the beginning of the end of the Gaza Empire.
In the past, a hippopotamus was hunted and its meat was distributed among the population to commemorate the date.
Today, hippopotamus meat has been replaced by goat meat, which is often enjoyed with a local drink called "canhu" - consumed while dancing to the sound of the marrabenta.
The history and evolution of the marrabenta was not easy.
It emerged in southern Mozambique in the late 1930s, but it wasn't until the 1960s that it became more popular.
Multiracial and multicultural policies within the Portuguese colonies in Africa facilitated its expansion in Mozambique and its cities.
The arrival of the first phonographs in South Africa and the emergence of local music broadcasts also contributed to their spread.
The legendary Dilon Djindji during his performance at the I Marrabenta Festival.
This is a photo of Quiroz afribuku.
Fighting music
The Portuguese regime in Mozambique demanded that only Portuguese music be sung and danced during most of the colonial period.
To defend their cultural identity, several organizations emerged, such as the African Association (AA) and the associative Centre of Negroes of the Province of Mozambique (CANPM), which ended up playing a fundamental role in promoting Mozambican culture.
In this way, marrabenta became a fight music whose themes are inspired by everyday life experiences, love, social criticism and important events that took place in Mozambique.
It's a good thing we're in the African Association (AA).
Photo from the personal file of Elarne and Fredo Cariano.
The evolution of the marrabenta
The rhythm was first played with homemade four-string guitars made from empty reed and wood pieces.
The mix of magikay and zukuta rhythms from the south of the country and the assimilation of Western rhythms such as black American and South African music that reached the ancient Lourenço Marques (now Maputo), enriched this new genre.
It didn't have a name until 1930, but it eventually adopted the name of marrabenta.
Sam Mangwana of the Democratic Republic of Congo (formerly Zaire, when he was born) arrived at the festival for the first time this year.
Marrabenta Festival 2013. Afiche published in afribuku.
It's been five years since the first edition of the Marrabenta Festival, thanks to the initiative of Litho Sithoe.
And five years later, the festival continues through the determination and perseverance of its organizer.
On February 3, the festival ended with a concert at the Cultural Center of the city of Matalane.
This day is celebrated as "Mozambique Heroes' Day", a national holiday commemorating the lives of fallen soldiers who fought valiantly for the country's independence in 1975.
The final touch to end a weekend breathing, living and feeling great.
No one can predict the future of the brass band or figure out how the style will evolve in modern times, if it will take its path to a more commercial sound.
But what's clear is that in this sixth edition, entertainment was guaranteed.
