Wikipedia, copyright and freedom of expression on the internet
Note: This article was originally published on the Digital Rights website.
It's no exaggeration to say that Wikipedia has revolutionized the way we create and access information, showing a sustainable and collaborative model of intellectual work and understanding phenomena such as intellectual property.
This platform has made it possible for us all to relate to knowledge in a different way and has also put in place closed models of access to knowledge.
In this new testimony from #NotemasaInternet about copyright on the network, we spoke with Osmar Valdebenito, president of Wikimedia Argentina (and former president of its Chilean version), a foundation that is responsible for coordinating and making Wikipedia's infrastructure possible globally.
We talked with him not only about how Wikimedia works, but how freedom of expression on the web is fundamental to its development and how initiatives that seek to be even stricter with copyright on the Internet (SOPA, PIPA, etc.), would make it impossible for Wikipedia to exist as we know it.
Video: A course on Islam for humanitarian organizations
This post is part of our Global Development special coverage.
A constant debate in the Uncultured Project has been the relationship between a lack of knowledge about what Islam is and how cooperation and development organizations are related to the Muslim community.
Shawn Ahmed has shared a video that explains, briefly and simply, what Islam is all about to try to pave the way for understanding a large group of people who might receive help.
In Shawn Ahmed's April 7, 2012, post Cooperation, Cynicism and Islam, he referred to another Muslim post explaining what Islam consists of and excludes cynicism as well as respect for others.
I hope that more cooperatives (especially those who work in countries where there are many Muslims) understand this and respect it.
In a November 2012 post on Islam and the Internet Cooperation and Development Discourse, Ahmed reflects how discussions about internet cooperation exclude minorities, even those minorities who are the subject of the same cooperation initiatives in question.
He considers that one of the reasons for this exclusion could be that the tone of these cooperation talks does not reflect cultural norms, and this could be influencing the bad image that the cooperative industry is generating, especially in the case of a Muslim-majority country like Bangladesh:
If the co-operatives agree and applaud that tone... then maybe they're right.
In another post from the Uncultured Project: Islam:101, Ahmed proposes that a greater understanding of the culture of the communities in which cooperation organizations focus could provide these same organizations with a better environment where, instead of rejecting some work with certain groups due to ignorance and discrimination, they could learn the culture and work from this basis.
