China: interactive maps of the most polluted and least polluted places
This article, written by Eli Bildner, first appeared in the Tea Leaf Nation on February 20, 2013 and is republished as part of a content sharing agreement.
Nearly five weeks ago, Beijing experienced the worst air quality day on record: PM2.5 levels  small particles that can cause lung, cardiovascular and respiratory diseases  rose more than 30 times above the level that the World Health Organization considers safe.
Air quality in China  Instant
Since then, there have been reports of the air apocalypse alongside what appears to be a black and white image of the country's iconic cities Beijing, Shanghai, Tianjin, all wrapped in a thick toxic fog.
In fact, China's most popular and prosperous cities are among the epicentres of the latest pollution crisis.
In Tianjin, for example, PM2.5 levels affected 577 people on February 9, the eve of the Chinese New Year.
In Beijing, sales of New Year's fireworks fell 37 percent after the municipal government asked residents to limit use.
But air quality in China is also a national problem  a difficult situation affecting cities with less recognition than Beijing or Shanghai.
Last week, Peoples Daily reported that 74 major cities, which the Chinese Ministry of Environmental Protection monitors, reported on February 10, the first day of the Chinese New Year, about "excessive" concentrations of PM2.5.
And as a glance at pollution, the figures this morning (February 20) show that dangerous air conditions continue throughout China, from Urumchi (with a PM2.5 concentration of 511 micrograms per cubic meter, or 20 times the recommended limit) to Canton.
