New methods for reducing poverty are being explored
Several Global Voices bloggers took charge of the live blogging of the OECD Global Forum on Development in Paris on 4 and 5 April 2013.
Prior to the meeting, our team published several articles on development issues to serve as content for weekly debates on their website (#OECDgfd)
Tissue for sale at the Makola market in Accra, Ghana.
Photo by Caroline Beaumont published by Transaid on flickr (CC BY-NC 2.0)
As the 2015 deadline for achieving the United Nations Millennium Development Goals (MDGs) approaches, the search for solutions to reduce poverty is on the rise.
Many organizations explore new answers in the hope that they will bring forth fresh ideas.
Among these goals agreed by the international community more than a decade ago was to halve the number of people who are hungry, and to get the world's poorest citizens productive jobs.
Many of the targets are far from being met in most countries, but progress has been made.
For example, in sub-Saharan Africa, where the proportion of people living on less than $1.25 a day fell from 58 percent to 51 percent between 1990 and 2005.
Exchange of ideas on the Internet
As every year, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) will hold its Global Forum on Development in Paris on 4 and 5 April 2013.
This year, the OECD wants to explore more inclusive methods for tackling poverty, inviting an open online debate ahead of the forum with OECD researchers.
The main topics of discussion have been made public so that everyone can know about them and contribute.
Concerned African Scholars, an organization of African thinkers and students, hosts another interesting way of sharing ideas online.
Among the many issues being discussed is the impact of the billions of dollars that are illegally leaving Africa because of the slow pace of poverty reduction.
If Africa had not lost so many resources in the form of illicit financial transfers, poverty would likely be much less rampant.
Logic says that keeping these resources in Africa would have produced higher investment rates, allowing African countries to spend money on sectors that promote productivity, such as infrastructure, job creation and income growth, which would have resulted in lower poverty levels.
This strategy of involving different stakeholders is also a fundamental principle of the open data movement, which is gradually entering the development sphere.
The Uganda Open Development Partnership Platform, a public initiative rooted in civil society, is an example of what open data can contribute to the debate on poverty reduction:
Open development increases transparency and accountability about the resources that can be invested in development, how those resources are invested and the results they achieve.
In the end, all stakeholders involved in this information exchange  data owners and users  benefit from this mutually reinforcing ecosystem
