Talking to Marianna Breytman, translator at Global Voices
During the last Global Voices Summit in Nairobi, Kenya, I met some (relatively) new Global Voices contributors.
One of them was Marianna Breytman, who translates from Spanish into English, so she is an avid reader of what we publish in Global Voices in Spanish by Latin American and Spanish authors.
I spoke to her quite informally and in the following short video you can see (and hear her) talking about Global Voices, translations and languages:
After that we were in contact via email, via which we talked about the following:
Juan Arellano: You just passed the 100 translated posts barrier for GV, was it something you set out to do when you started?
Marianna Breytman: No, I'm not going to.
The truth is, when I started Global Voices, I didn't know where it was going to take me.
I was just doing the translations because it was something I liked to do, it was fun, like I told you in Nairobi.
The 100 posts thing came up when I was approaching my 2nd anniversary with GV (in March 2013) and I wanted to get 100 posts before that.
JA: Any of the translations you've done for GV have impacted you or do you have anecdotes related to them?
MB: The translations that really impress me are those that take place in places I've known. I remember a post Ariel had written about the "red devils" in Panama just after I had made my trip to that country.
I knew I had to translate that post because I had just had that experience of seeing them all over the city.
There's another post I remember from Robert about the protests in Brooklyn after the death of Kimani Gray.
I didn't even know this was happening in my own town until I took over the translation.
When Elaine was denied a visa (*) to come to the US, she posted a post on her blog with her reaction to it.
She wanted to spread it out and I immediately told her I'd translate it.
I was so sad to read his moving story and learn more about his situation, as a colleague and friend, that I was inspired to make the best translation I could.
At that moment, I realized the importance of doing translations to give a voice to people who want to tell their stories to the rest of the world.
That's why I love what I do.
JA: Since Spanish isn't your native language, how did you get interested in this language?
MB: Everyone asks me that, and I still don't have a good answer! I've been studying Spanish for many, many years, since I was a kid in elementary school, but I think the first time I got interested was when I was in the sixth grade, and I had a Spanish teacher who was an Orthodox Jew from Panama (that's the beauty of living in New York City!).
I think he saw something in me that I didn't even recognize and pushed me to keep learning the language.
Thanks to him, I started reading more, listening to more radio in Spanish, and taking advanced classes.
But learning Spanish never seemed like that.
I went to study it because I didn't feel like I was making a big effort to learn it.
I was just doing something I liked.
This is Marianna Breytman.
JA: Since you're a volunteer for GV, what other things do you do your time on?
I specifically work on the Au Pair program that gives opportunities for students living abroad to come to the U.S. to care for children and study at the same time.
My position is International Recruitment Coordinator, so I review all applicant applications and work with our international partners to help them spread the program in their country.
Besides that, I sometimes teach Spanish at a collaborative education center in Brooklyn.
JA: I read that you're very interested in gastronomy -- do you cook in your spare time?
MB: Where did you read that?!
I'm interested in gastronomy, but I don't cook as much as I would like, I'm very interested in trying out different countries.
I was in Panama for the first time in March (and I had the opportunity to visit another GV'er, the wonderful Ariel Moreno) and I ate my first ceviche.
JA: You're quite young, what are your plans for the future?
MB: For now, I would very much like to continue working in the field of international education.
I'm fascinated by this subject of mixing and coexisting cultures, which is why I love living in New York.
Then, for the future, I've thought about working for an organization that is dedicated to fighting for human rights and/or doing economic development projects.
I also want to continue teaching Spanish.
And obviously I look forward to continuing to work with Global Voices.
I'd like to diversify and learn more about other projects within GV as well.
In fact, I just did some translations for Eddie at Rising Voices and that gave me the opportunity to learn more about that part of the organization.
I have also been working voluntarily with WITNESS (one of GV's partners who makes videos to fight for human rights) for over a year and plan to continue helping them and translating for their initiatives.
In the following video we talked a little more about Global Voices and the meeting that led us to Nairobi.
JA: Anything else to add?
MB: Yes, thanks to Firuzeh and Silvia, I hope to continue to develop and grow as a translator with them.
The truth is, I never thought in my life that, as a volunteer translator, I would have the opportunity to be part of this GV family and meet so many amazing people who are changing the world.
It was a dream, really.
