Spark13: Fourth world forum on telecentres
Rising Voices is pleased to announce that it will be a media partner at the Fourth World Forum on Telecentres to be held in Granada, Spain, from 28 to 29 May 2013.
This meeting called Spark 13 will focus on three main themes of discussion: People, innovation and sustainability.
Participants in the Global Telecentre Network, which consists of approximately 500,000 telecentres serving around one billion users worldwide, will be able to participate in small group sessions, workshops and other participatory activities to explore the topics of discussion.
According to Telecentre.org:
A telecentre is a public place where people can find information, create, learn and communicate with others, while developing digital skills through access to information and communication technology.
Organized by the Telecentre.org Foundation, Telecentres Europe, the Fernando de los Rios-Red Guadalinfo Consortium, and the National Agency of the Korean Information Society, Spark13 hopes to bring together 1,300 participants from around the world.
The winners of the Telecentre Global First Awards will be announced on Spark13.
Awards will be presented in the following categories: Telecentro, Telecentro Manager, Telecentro Network, Telecentros Iniciativa, Telecentro Innovación, Information and Access Centre.
Rising Voices has been very interested in how physical spaces, such as telecenters, libraries and hacker labs can be important resources for local communities as a way to foster citizen engagement through the use of digital media tools.
Providing access to the Internet is certainly an important step, but many of these spaces also provide important training and mentoring for users.
In August 2012, together with New Tactics and Social Media Exchange, Rising Voices organized an online dialogue called "Physical Spaces as Catalysts for Greater Digital Citizenship Participation".
During this virtual conversation, we gathered experts and other professionals to share their experiences, challenges and success stories:
Around the world, the new physical spaces that are emerging act as catalysts for greater citizen participation through digital technologies.
Community libraries are rethinking their traditional role, and many are offering internet access to their users in order to provide opportunities to meet on local issues, where they can produce and not just consume information.
Telecentres go beyond providing computer access to communities, they offer workshops to train citizens on how to use digital technology effectively to promote change.
Hacklabs offer a physical space where activists and technologists can come together to find innovative solutions to local problems.
These are just a few examples of the innovative use of physical space to encourage and enhance greater participation of digital citizenship.
Before, during and after Spark 13, Rising Voices will be presenting some of these innovative telecenters that are playing a major role in helping communities access local digital media tools to tell their own stories or participate more fully online.
Mozambique: Land development and appropriation programmes
Amid growing concern about "land ownership" in Africa and the transformation of the smallholder system into large-scale commercial agriculture, a controversial economic development plan was leaked and alarmed both Mozambique, Brazil and Japan, two key investors.
According to the Mozambican NGO "Environmental Justice" and other signatory organizations, a leaked copy of the so-called Master Plan of the pro-SABANA program dated March 2013, reveals plans for "land appropriation" by the governments of Japan, Brazil and Mozambique.
A Mozambican peasant.
Photo published under CC BY-NC 2.0 license, by Flickr Bread for the World user.
Brazilian activist Fátima Mello explains the pro-SABANA project and tells us the story of the program in an interview with the Humanitas Institute:
Pro SABANA is a cooperation and investment programme involving three countries: Brazil, Japan and Mozambique.
It is an agricultural plan comprising three provinces in northern Mozambique, a 14.5 million hectare region where about 5.5 million farmers live and produce their food within a family farm system.
Pro SABANA is derived from the Prodecer programme, which was developed in Mato Grosso, in the Brazilian "closed" area in the 1980s, with the cooperation of Japan and which had the characteristics we already know in the closed area: giant large-scale mono-culture soybeans for export, intensive use of pesticides, elimination of traditional crops, land concentration, soil pollution and the creation of economic power in land and agro-industries, which translated into political power...
The region, the "Nacala corridor", is the size of Switzerland and Austria combined.
The government and the bodies sponsoring this project had not yet shown maps where farmers and citizens in general could see the land that would be included.
The farmers' organisations were completely excluded from the design of policies and the project.
The National Union of Peasants of Mozambique (UNAC) declared last year:
We, the poor farmers, condemn the way in which the pro-SABANA programme was designed and the way in which it is intended to be implemented in Mozambique, as there was a lack of transparency and civil organisations were excluded from the process, especially farmers' organisations.
In Delegoa Bay's blog, a blogger named ABM writes:
Talking to the farmers of the Nacala corridor makes it clear that Brazilians and Japanese are visiting the communities to warn them that the Pro SABANA plan will begin to be implemented.
Then they'll say they consulted civil society.
What they're doing is not consulting.
In March, under increasing pressure, the Mozambican government declared that "dialogue must be permanent".
Brazilian diplomats responded to the transparency request by ensuring that the peasants will be included in the development plans of the Nacala corridor.
The director of the Brazilian Cooperation Agency, Fernando Abreu, said last month that more information about the project will be given and that there were no plans to displace the farmers from the land.
The leakage of the programme made it possible to know the maps showing the districts that will be allocated for large-scale agriculture for export purposes and allowed civil organizations to verify exactly which communities would be affected to have a clearer idea of the potential impact.
The document identifies seven areas of intensive development.
Environmental Justice and other signatory organisations describe the type of agriculture to be launched.
Some projects in the programme grant large areas of land to investors.
The grain-producing zone projected in the district of Majune in the province of Niassa will be managed by a vertical integration company that will manage nine farms of 5,000 ha each, in a region that has 60,000 ha in total, and will be turned into corn, soybean and sunflower crops, mainly destined for export.
The programme assures that 'the project has a high rate of return; the internal rate of return is calculated at 20.3% and the amortisation in 9 years'.
Organizations continue to wonder if there will be any benefit to Mozambicans in the region:
It is significant that only one of the seven regions of the Master Plan is for farmers and family production.
And in this area only the same old and wrong model of development of the green revolution is proposed.
The Master Plan has not taken into account the needs or capabilities of the peasants in the Nacala corridor.
Corporations are the major beneficiaries of the Master Plan.
They will have control over the land, production and trade of the food produced, which will be transported through the roads, trains and the port of Nacala, which other foreign corporations will build with public funds from Mozambique and Japan.
The National Union of Peasants predicted last year that many problems would arise from the Pro SABANA program: landless peasants, social unrest, impoverishment, corruption, contaminated water and ecological imbalance due to deforestation.
The Union warns that all this could happen if the project continues as planned.
