VIDEO: Reflective Brazilian boy doesn't want to eat meat
The YouTube video of three-year-old Luiz Antonio explaining to his mother why he doesn't want to eat octopus noodles has become the most recent video worldwide.
The Brazilian boy claims that he does not like eating meat because "when you eat animals, they die", and that he likes to see animals "standing, happy", and explains that we must "take care of them, not eat them".
The original Portuguese video, uploaded to YouTube on May 15, 2013, has already had about 1,500,000 views in just two weeks.
The English version was published on May 29 and within three days had been viewed more than 900,000 times.
In a country where only a very small percentage of the population has opted for a vegetarian diet, the viral video has sparked a heated debate about vegetarianism on YouTube and Facebook.
Carlos Augusto Andrade explained the reasons:
The video went viral on Facebook yesterday, it's one of those that you share with all kinds of people: your mother, your aunt, your sophisticated friends, your school contacts... and while some groups on Facebook and YouTube have used the video to discuss vegetarianism, we understand that it's only gone viral because it is: the cute video of a child who is curiously eloquent for his age and reflects on something that we don't all bother to stop and think about.
Philosophy of Luiz Antonio: "When we eat animals, they die.
I don't like that, I like to see them standing, happy.
We must take care of them, not eat them".
Inspired by the simplicity of the child's argument, some people have decided to adopt a meatless lifestyle, like many of the friends with whom blogger Viviane Zandonadi shared the video.
As a food writer, she wondered what she'd do with her daughter when she started asking these kinds of questions:
I'm really looking forward to it.
When it's my turn, if Cata questions the logic of the food chain, I have no idea what I'm gonna say.
Luiz Antonio has knocked my arguments down.
At the end of the video, Luiz Antonio's mother, moved to tears, asks her son to eat only rice and potatoes.
In the blog Acerto de Contas, Guilherme Carvalho hopes that other parents will start respecting their children's sensitivities, and stop using lies or simplistic arguments to force children to change their minds:
So in 2013, it's time to stop fooling our children and suppressing their feelings of compassion when they don't show a penchant for eating animals.
Let us respect and value this altruistic and compassionate attitude.
Having a vegetarian child is not a problem, and today there is extensive literature showing the potential health benefits of this option.
Luiz Antonio's video has left many people moved - and hopeful.
The Caribbean flu scare originated accidentally in China.
What's in a name with a couple of numbers and letters?
It turns out that a lot, when those letters and numbers refer to a strain of the influenza virus (flu).
While it is not critical to know your hemaglutinin from your neuraminidase (the two proteins at the origin of the conventions for the "H" and "N" flu names), as the National Pork Board states in its guidelines for influenza names (PDF): "Knowing the proper name of a flu virus is important to adjust to the facts and avoid misinterpretation and an inappropriate response".
Specific case: the confusion of the first week of June of avian/swine flu, which had officials from Trinidad and Tobago pointing to Venezuela after (unfounded) concerns about avian flu following a visit by an official delegation headed by Chinese President Xi Jinping, and officials in Haiti who imposed a ban on the import of meat and chicken products from its neighbor, the Dominican Republic.
The likely source of this confusion, according to Canadian novelist and blogger Crawford Kilian, was a poor translation from Chinese to English by Xinhua, the official Chinese news agency.
The first clue, detected by Kilian on June 6, 2013 and reported in a blog post titled "H7N9 in the Caribbean? Unlikely", was a report on Trinidad Express that Kilian described as "the least likely story since the outbreak began".
The Express article focused on a "suspicious" case of avian influenza in Trinidad and Tobago, and reported that "questions were beginning to arise" about the reasons why members of the 153-person delegation that accompanied Chinese President Xi Jinping on an official visit to Trinidad in the first week of June were not screened for avian influenza upon entry into the country, given that "China is currently fighting an avian influenza pandemic .
The article quoted Trinidad and Tobago's Health Minister as saying that although there was no "outbreak" of avian influenza in the country, certainly Trinidad and Tobago was susceptible due to its proximity to Venezuela.
"The idea that important members of the Chinese government are carrying H7N9 is simply absurd, unless we assume that President Xi and his colleagues also have additional income as chicken traders.
China is not "fighting a bird flu pandemic".
The reported Chinese deaths and case numbers don't make sense.
And no matter what the bunch of cases they have in Venezuela, they're not H7N9 or H5N1".
On the same day, Kilian reported finding the likely source of the bad information: an article by China's official news agency, Xinhua, titled "A bird flu virus infects 724 people in Venezuela".
The Haiti Observer blog, from Florida, had a similar error in a June 7 post about the Haitian government's ban on importing chicken and other meat products from its neighboring Dominican Republic, where, according to the article, a warning has been issued "concerning the bird flu outbreak (H1N1 virus)  (the highlight is ours).
The error was reproduced in the French-language Haitian newspaper Le Nouvelliste.
The Dominican Republic exports 25 million eggs and eight million chickens to Haiti each year.
Although there was certainly an outbreak of the H2N2 strain of avian influenza in the Dominican Republic in 2008, Dominican officials have been adamant that the country is currently free of avian influenza, and claim that the five flu deaths have been due to swine flu, which has no impact on the quality of local meat exports.
