FOTOS: Police violence against protesters and bystanders in Rio de Janeiro
This publication is part of our special coverage of the Vinegar Revolt in Brazil.
A week ago, on the afternoon of June 20, 2013, Brazil was rocked by the largest wave of protest in its recent history.
In Rio de Janeiro, an event that began as a peaceful demonstration from the city center to the city hall spread to other neighborhoods and ended in violent clashes between police and protesters.
According to official estimates, about 300,000 people took part in the demonstration in Rio de Janeiro.
Among them is the Brazilian photographer Calé who recorded in a photo reportage the indiscriminate use of rubber bullets, pepper spray and tear gas by the police against unarmed protesters.
The result is the testimonial and photos below, carefully selected by Calé for Global Voices Online:
At the beginning of the demonstration people danced and celebrated on the way to the town hall, there was joy.
Photo:Calé, authorized release
A violent group started a fight with left-wing party supporters, the police reacted slowly and stopped no one.
Photo:Calé, authorized release
There were some minor incidents, such as a fight between left-wing party supporters and young people who did not want the demonstration to be exploited or connected to any political party.
A man wounded in the demonstration helped by other protesters.
Photo:Calé, authorized release
Protesters make a criminal human chain of police to avoid conflict and try to keep the protest peaceful.
Photo:Calé, authorized release
The leaders of the demonstration made a human chain in front of the police to avoid conflicts, to ensure that a small group of agitators did not spoil an afternoon of such pleasant demonstrations.
Bodybuilder Gabriel Campos kissing a police officer's horse in an attempt to provoke.
Photo:Calé, authorized release
The protesters managed to keep the protest peaceful in front of the town hall, until a 29-year-old bodybuilder, Gabriel Campos, who is now wanted by the police, began insulting the police who were on their horses, despite people asking him to get away from there.
At one point, protesters asked the police to stop him before it was too late.
The protesters used wooden panels as a shield and threw stones at the police.
