China orders older children to visit their parents
China has enacted a new law this week that requires older children to visit their parents often.
In China, it is a firm tradition to respect the elderly and to care for parents when they get older, but modern lifestyles have led young people to leave their homes to pursue their careers and their mate.
The new law says adults should care for their parents' spiritual needs and that they should never neglect the elderly, but it does not specify how often they should visit their parents or what punishment they will receive if they do not.
The law is passed at a time when China's population is rapidly aging because of the one-child policy.
The journal reported that more than 14 percent of China's population, or 194 million people, are over the age of 60, according to the latest National Bureau of Statistics studies.
In addition, since 2012, China's pension system has been in crisis, with a deficit of $2.9 trillion.
Young Chinese people fear they will end up having to support government pensioners.
The new law has sparked mockery on China's most popular microblogging website, Sina Weibo, where many people joked that enforcing the law is questionable, and visiting parents should be a moral issue that should be encouraged, not demanded by law.
Some users complained that they didn't have enough free time to visit their parents even if they wanted to, while others thought the law was made to compensate for the Chinese pension problem.
The Internet personality  Zhuomo Xiansheng  wrote sarcastically:
Image from Sina Weibo
Family ties must be based on spontaneous emotions.
It's funny that the law turns them into you: it's like demanding that couples have a good sex life after marriage.
Lawyer Yang Lei subscribed to this sentiment:
The question is how to enforce the law.
For example, will parents be given a fingerprinting machine?
Social security is mainly for civil servants, most ordinary people do not have a pension to cover.
TV host Cao Baoying thinks the law is a way for the government to evade its own responsibility:
By passing this law, it emphasizes unilateral civic duty, while lightening the responsibilities of the government.
