This post, written by Elisa Moreno Gili, is the second part of a series on the Chilean student revolts.
The original post, "The revolts of Chilean students: Chile mobilized (part 2) " was published in Ciudadano Periodismo.
As we have already mentioned in the first article on student movements in Chile and in the Movilized Chile, the creation of digital media in this region is already a deeply rooted practice.
In September 2005, citizen journalists from Chile, Peru and Mexico, among others, began to awaken in the Chilean population a desire to communicate beyond traditional media.
Inspired by the South Korean media OhMyNews and driven by former senator Fernando Flores and the Atina Chile movement, they created El Morrocotudo.
This newspaper, which is still in operation today, has had a major impact on the creation of other local citizen media less influenced by the senator's initial figure, such as Maulee.
The perception of whistleblowers in Chile about information management largely reflects the assimilation of citizen journalism among the population.
The use of traditional media by Chile Movilizado is considered a positive impact that should reinforce the work that the collaborators are doing.
