Early in the film, Delacourt orders a ruthless downing of a spacecraft full of immigrants in an attempt to enter Elysium.
The Commission notes that the Commission has not yet established a specific measure to prevent the entry of illegal immigrants into the Union.
Just as Elysium is unraveling, one might think that the main reason these "illegal" want to flee planet Earth for a more comfortable life in Elysium is parallel to the reason why many immigrants decide to cross the border and find a better life in the United States (of course, the U.S. is the Elysium for all hopeful immigrants abroad).
The film also shows that immigrants go to Elysium to find a better healthcare system, but they need to be citizens of Elysium to benefit from it.
In real life, many undocumented immigrants face the same problem, given that they do not have access to health care.
Before we get into the weeds of immigration debate, blogs like ThinkProgress explain that Elysium is short on why the healthcare system on the space satellite is better than the Earth:
But the more you think about it, the more you convince yourself that Elysium is not able to tell the truth, that it's not really like it's the way things are because it's not able to answer a simple question: why is there so little Earth health care in Elysium's world?
The film shows us many ways in which life on Elysium is more comfortable and satisfying than on Earth, but Blomkamp focuses almost exclusively on inhabitants of planet Earth who aspire to reach Elysium primarily to access medical equipment capable of curing them, even from serious illnesses, with a simple and quick scan".
ThinkProgress goes on to say:
And at the end of the movie, they get it.
Spider and Max download a program on Elysium's central computer that turns everyone on Earth into citizens of Elysium and thus enables them to be scanned by devices, launchers full of these equipment are sent to Earth, where people of all races, sexes and religions can use them.
The problem does not seem to be the shortage of medical equipment.
There might be other reasons for this restriction in health care, but whatever the reasons may be are not clear in the film".
Applying this last paragraph to real life can mean that legalizing the immigration situation of 11 million people in the United States will ensure a better quality of life for all of them.
As the Immigration Policy Center notes:
Granting health care to legal immigrants not only strengthens the system but is a crucial part of their integration into American society.
In addition to working, paying taxes and learning English, immigrants must be able to pay their contribution and receive affordable health care, like everyone else".
When asked if the film shows what human conditions will be like in 140 years, Blomkamp replied:
No, no, no, I'm not going to.
This is not science fiction.
This is now".
As for immigration, Blomkamp might be right.
Elysium portrays the United States as a country that has been overtaken by Latin Americans and whose native language of iure is Spanish, at a time when the badges of local offices and factories contain writing in Spanish, and where law enforcement is referred to as "Police".
Finally, there is one thing we can deduce from the film and that is that no society, however perfect it claims to be, can turn a blind eye to its inhabitants and their needs - and addressing the issue of immigration is the first step toward understanding human history.
