'Million People's March' Against Corruption in the Philippines
Mass protests, the largest since President Benigno 'Noynoy' Aquino III took office three years ago, shook the Philippines, on National Heroes Day, August 26, when hundreds of thousands expressed outrage at government corruption and called for a total abolition of money donation to political candidates.
Police estimated that between 80,000 and 100,000 people gathered at Rizal Park in the country's capital, Manila, while thousands more carried out mass actions in other cities nationwide.
Public outrage over such corrupt donations came after the disclosure of the Priority Development Assistance Fund (PDAF), which is allocated to legislators in Congress and the Senate to use in their favorite projects.
For a long time, the PDAF has been the target of criticism as an official corruption site.
But public outcry increased after a whistleblower identified businesswoman Janet Lim-Napoles, who is alleged to have conspired with lawmakers to pocket 10 billion Filipino pesos (about $22 million) through the fund.
Airshot of the Rizal Park rally.
Photo courtesy of the architect Paulo Alcazaren.
From @muntingprinsipe
Called the "Million People's March", the idea behind Monday's 26th meeting at Rizal Park, where middle-class people predominated, originated from social media interactions between concerned netizens on Facebook and Twitter.
The concept for a million-person march against donating money to political candidates began with a Facebook post by music producer Ito Rapadas:
What we need is a MARCH OF A MILLION PERSON by Filipino taxpayer-fighting, a day of silent majority protest that would demand that all politicians and government officials (whatever political bands or colors they have) stop pocketing our money from our hard work through these corruption traps and other creative criminal acts.
This was shared by several webmasters, including his friend Peachy Brittany, who suggested that the mass action be held on August 26, National Heroes Day.
Protests were also held in various cities nationwide, notably in Bacolod City, Baguio City, Cagayan de Oro, Cebu, Dagupan City, Davao City, Digos City, Dumaguete City, Iloilo City, Naga City and Puerto Princessa in Palawan.
"Let the 22 million dollars paid by President Aquino be redirected to social services". Photo by @LeanneJazul.
The protest action stood still.
