17 pieces of Nelson Mandela's wisdom that we all should read
Nelson Mandela was the first democratically elected president in South Africa.
Photo published by South Africa The Good News under Creative Commons license (CC BY 2.0).
Nelson Mandela, South Africa's first democratically elected president and Nobel Peace Prize winner, died on 5 December 2013 at the age of 95.
Mandela spent 27 years in prison for his struggle against South Africa's system of racial segregation known as apartheid. He was released from prison in 1990, and became president four years later, and left office after only serving for a period, a rare gesture in African politics.
One of his most famous phrases comes from a defiant speech he made in court during his Rivonia betrayal trial in 1964, where he said:
I've fought white domination and I've fought black domination.
I have treasured the ideal of a democratic and free society where all people live together in harmony with equal opportunity.
It's an ideal I hope to live for and achieve.
But if necessary, it's an ideal for which I'm prepared to die.
In addition to his speech at the Rivonia trial, Mandela leaves behind many memorable and wise phrases he said throughout his life.
On judgments
Don't judge me by my successes, judge me by how many times I fell and got up again. - Nelson Mandela
I'm not a saint unless you consider a sinner a saint who keeps trying. - Nelson Mandela
About hate
Hate clouds the mind.
Leaders cannot afford to hate.
If you can learn to hate, you can learn to love, for love comes more naturally to the human heart than the opposite.
Nobody is born hating Nelson Mandela.
About forgiveness
You will achieve more in this world through acts of kindness than through acts of retaliation.
About the sport
Sport can awaken hope where before there was only hopelessness.
On leadership
Drive from behind and let others think they're ahead.
On racism
I hate racism because I consider it a barbarism, whether it comes from a black man or a white man.
On the determination
It always seems impossible until it's done.
The brave man is not the one who is not afraid, but the one who conquers that fear. - Nelson Mandela, Long March to Freedom, 1994.
Honor belongs to those who never leave the truth, even when things seem dark and gloomy. - Nelson Mandela 1969.
About freedom
Because being free is not just throwing away chains, but living in a way that respects and encourages the freedom of others.
On education
Education is the most powerful weapon you can use to change the world.
About the prison
It's said that no one really knows a nation until they're inside its prisons.
On duty
When a man has done what he considers his duty to his people and his country, he can rest in peace. ~ Nelson Mandela.
Iceland mourns first case of man killed by police
Police in Reikiavik, Iceland.
Photo by Christopher Porter on flickr (CC BY-NC-ND 2.0)
This article and radio report by Traci Tong for The World originally appeared on PRI.org on December 3, 2013 and is republished as part of a content sharing agreement.
This week there has been an unprecedented headline in Iceland: a man died from police fire.
"The country is in shock.
This does not happen in our country", said Thóra Arnórsdóttir, news editor of RUV, the national Icelandic radio and television channel.
The man, who started shooting at the police when they entered the building where he lived, had a history of mental problems.
It's the first time anyone has been killed by armed police in Iceland since it became an independent republic in 1944.
The police don't even usually carry guns.
Violent crimes are almost nonexistent in the country.
"The country does not want its police force to carry weapons because it is dangerous, it is threatening", Arnórsdóttir says.
Weapons are used to hunt as a sport, but we never see weapons".
In fact, Iceland is not anti-gun. In terms of gun ownership per capita, Iceland ranks 15th on the world list. Still, this incident is so rare that the neighbors of the slain man compared the shooting to a scene from an American movie.
The Icelandic police department said the police involved will receive psychological support and has already apologized to the family of the deceased  although not because they did anything wrong.
"It's respectful", says Arnórsdóttir, "because nobody likes to take someone else's life".
There are still many questions to be answered, including why the police did not try to negotiate with the man before entering the building.
"One of the great things about living in this country is that you can enter parliament and all they ask you to do is turn off your mobile phone so you don't disturb parliamentarians while they're talking.
There are no armed guards following the Prime Minister or the President.
We don't want that to change".
