Uruguay became a "whale and dolphin sanctuary"
Photo shared by @PaipoUruguay on Twitter.
Uruguay passed in September the law 19.128, which declares the Uruguay's jurisdictional waters "Whale and Dolphin Sanctuary".
The law applies to the territorial sea and the Uruguay exclusive economic zone, and prohibits hunting, pursuit, appropriation, fishing or the subjecting of any cetacean to transformation processes.
It also prohibits the transport and landing of live whales or dolphins, both on national and foreign flag vessels.
The law provides for penalties for those who do not comply.
Cases of health or scientific interest, as endorsed by national authorities, shall be considered as exceptions.
The law also provides for cases of harassment, aggression or harassment that could lead to the death of the cetaceans.
The law was unanimously approved by the Legislative Power and was promulgated on September 13 by President José Mujica.
The law 19.128 would reinforce existing conservationist policies, carried out by the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries (MGAP) and the National Directorate of Water Resources (DINARA).
DINARA Director Daniel Gilardoni told the Presidency: For our country the biggest threat is navigation, much of the landings are due to the collisions of the boats with cetaceans
Declaring the Uruguayan waters a sanctuary for whales and dolphins would be economically beneficial, according to the article "Uruguay a sanctuary for whales and dolphins: Let the cetaceans come to me" in the blog Ballenas in Uruguay.
Popular opinion was favorable to the enactment of the law.
