Shall we start with the good news?
Photographed by Matthew Perkins on Flickr (CC BY-NC-ND 2.0)
Here's the good news: Over the years, Global Voices has brought you countless stories about hope, courage and human creativity from around the world.
Here's the bad news: Like other news sites, we're often guilty of focusing more on negative content and maybe we end up depressing you.
Do you normally have a positive expectation of reading Global Voices, or are you discouraged by being exposed to what would seem like an endless array of stories about injustice and human suffering?
In 2014, we plan to focus more on solution-oriented journalism.
So we hope to show more light to humanity than darkness and desolation.
This does not mean that we will ignore bad things, such as violence and poverty.
However, we want to set aside a space to showcase the positive developments.
In fact, we've already started doing it, by sharing stories like good news from Yemen that you didn't know about; or the news of millions of children in Bangladesh getting free textbooks; or how in Angola the internet is being used to preserve native languages.
Many of our stories focus on online social movements and citizens mobilizing to improve their societies.
We want to tell these stories in a way that inspires hope; we want to avoid falling into the same format as traditional media that focuses on the negative.
To begin with, we have created the "Good News" category on Global Voices.
In late December, we organized a GV Face conversation between GV Co-Founder Ethan Zuckerman, Vice Editor Sahar H. Ghazi, Advocacy Editor Ellery Biddle and a server, to discuss the topic of a positive approach to stories in GV.
This will be a long-term effort that will gradually change the way we tell stories together with our authors and editors. We are following the example of many other journalistic sites and organizations that are pioneering in reporting with positive headlines, projecting solution-oriented journalism, conducting constructive reporting and other similar resources.
Even the Huffington Post already has a Good News section (although you'll probably find more cute pet stories there than on Global Voices).
The world we want you to know through Global Voices is beautiful.
It's inhabited by brave, creative individuals who believe the planet can be a better place.
Perhaps through this change we can give our readers a sense of how they can contribute too.
Take a look at the Good News section and share with us what you would like to see on Global Voices.
