Photo by Simenon on Flickr, under Creative Commons license (CC BY-SA 2.0) In Argentina, Paraguay and Uruguay it is a popular tradition to eat gnocchi on the 29th of each month.
It is not known for certain where or how this custom comes from, but many bloggers have devoted their space and recipes to why and how to do it.
The blog section of Why goes back to the 8th century:
The tradition of serving gnocchi on the 29th day is born from a legend that dates back to the 8th century.
At that time in Nicosia (Greater Asia) lived a young doctor named Pantaleon, who, after converting to Christianity, made a pilgrimage to northern Italy.
There he performed miraculous healings for which he was canonized.
On one occasion he asked some peasants for bread, and they invited him to share their poor table.
Thankfully, he announces a year of excellent fishing and harvesting.
The prophecy was fulfilled and many other miracles.
San Pantaleon was consecrated - along with San Marco - patron saint of Venice.
That episode was on the 29th, so that's why we remember that day with a simple meal represented by the Nooki.
The ritual of putting money under the plate symbolizes the desire for new gifts.
Carambolatango has its favorite story:
During the European War, in Italy, food was scarce then.
The government distributed bonds that were exchanged for food on expenses.
The larger families found themselves in serious difficulty in feeding and reaching the end of the month.
Solidarity between the people was born and the neighbors invited the larger families to eat noquis, which was always considered food for the poor.
They put a bonus under each plate and this gift allowed these groups to trade them for food and get to the end of the month -
In turn, Chocolate and Rambus Moglia Alejandra adds another version of the story:
Another story tells that about 1690, in a village in Piedmont, the wheat harvest was lost.
While potatoes were used only to feed animals, they were so miserable that they cooked them, mixed them with flour, and gave rise to the nooki.
Nuria Eme of Recipes Book publishes a recipe for how to make them and adds:
They usually eat on the 29th of each month, and apparently the origin (of this version, because there are several) is that because it was one of the last days of the month, people who had few resources and were charging the first of the month, had to engineer them to eat with food made from cheap raw materials.
And of course, we already know that potatoes and flour are not overly expensive.
And although the tradition is ancient, I think it is unfortunately extrapolating in time, and totally current with the circumstances we have had to live in.
But tradition went beyond meals.
In Argentina, public employees and those employees who do not work but are paid their salary on the 29th of each month are nicknamed "ñoquis".
