In Cuba, as everywhere else, everything but wages increase
Food prices have risen in Cuba in recent times, while the wages of state workers remain the same. (Photo courtesy of the author)
The recently concluded congress of the Central of Workers of Cuba, the only organization of its kind in the country, concluded with the confirmation that there will be no increase in wages for state workers in Cuba until productivity increases.
In this country, the average wage of state workers amounts to 15 dollars a month (according to the exchange rate of the official Cuban currency) and living costs have increased over the past years, following the implementation of economic measures such as the elimination of some basic food from the basket subsidized by the State.
This is in addition to the significant increase in food prices on the non-State market.
According to Cuban President Raul Castro,
It would be irresponsible and counterproductive to have a widespread increase in wages in the public sector, since the only thing that would cause it would be an inflationary spiral in prices, if it is not duly supported by a sufficient increase in the supply of goods and services.
The conditioning of wage increases to productivity increases brings the debate on the subject in Cuba back to the vicious circle in which it has been in recent times.
In this regard, the newly elected secretary of the organization, Ulises Guilarte, noted that in not a few places this is noted as:
... cause of dismotivation, apathy and disinterest in work, with the consequent impacts on labour discipline, the exodus of skilled workers to better paid but less demanding activities from the professional point of view, undoubtedly resulting in a process of decapitalisation of the workforce, which has mainly impacted the basic industrial branches, the Ministry of Construction and others, in addition to the increasingly frequent refusal to be promoted to management responsibilities.
In his speech, Raúl Castro confirmed that medical services will receive a salary increase, "because the country's basic income at this time obeys the work of thousands of doctors providing services abroad".
In January 2011, the Brazilian ambassador to Havana announced that this year there will be 11,000 Cuban doctors in his country working in the poorest and hardest-to-reach areas.
This South-South cooperation is endorsed by the Pan American Health Organization and will provide about $500 million dollars annually to Cuba.
From his blog, Esquinas de Cuba, Alejandro Ulloa says that:
If we do not achieve abundant foreign investment, as well as recapitalization of important productive sectors, the Cuban economy will be moving in this vicious circle, which is all the more concerned about the increase in the purchasing power of wages, a real problem affecting the population today.
