I then exist: messages in local languages
A few days ago, I was chatting with a good friend of mine on the BlackBerry messaging platform.
We were talking about specialized topics, and we were doing it in Nigerian pidgin.
I'm not a Nigerian, but living with a large community of Nigerians teaches.
While we were talking I was frustrated because my phone's self-correction function insisted on correcting the interjection  na  to  N'a , or it completed the expression  sha  as  shame .
So I impulsively opened the language settings, and when he asked me to choose a language, I laughed, because I realized the pointlessness: pidgin is not on the list of languages of any modern electronic platform.
Screenshot of  Yoruba Keyboard , an application that replaces the keyboard to be able to write in Yoruba, a language available in the Windows Phone OS.
Photo from Nuges Apps licensed under CC BY 2.0.
So I thought about it and I asked myself why?
According to user data from the Nigerian Communications Commission, Nigeria has about 122 million connected and active telephone lines, of which 97% are mobile lines, making the country the first in this category in Africa and ninth in the world.
Still, the most common language in Nigeria is not available in phone settings.
However, this problem is not unique to Nigeria.
Around the world, dialects and vehicular languages (lingua franca) less widespread than official languages are underrepresented in the technological world.
For example, Urdu is the national and vehicle language of Pakistan, and is the official language in five Indian states.
In Africa, however, several dialects of the Bantu family, with similar prevalence, are not present on mobile devices.
There are third-party apps and plugins to help native speakers feel more comfortable with their smartphones.
Among those projects, Kannada-Hindi Keyboard allows its users to type from messages to notes in Kannada and Devanagari (Marathi/Hindi) script from India, and Multiling Keyboard is a keyboard application for Android that accepts around 130 languages.
But the developers of these applications often suffer from a lack of funding and lack of consumer support, which often leads to them abandoning the project.
Or does the world think that these languages have no place in the advanced technology sector?
Hopefully, in the years ahead, we will have Android or iOS platforms that allow us to customize the root user interface, including keyboard and data input settings in Pashtun and Igbo languages.
